@aturon Alright, I'll look into it. One worry is that I think it may not be possible to `Int`/`Float` right off the bat, because they are used as bounds in some places (libtest comes to mind). So, I'll add the `impl u8/f32/etc` but leave those traits around. We can decide how to deal with them later, perhaps move them to rust-lang/num? Since I think libtest will also be moved out of rust-lang/rust.

@alexcrichton 

> could you give the primitive pages a quick glance to make sure all the methods are listed?

I can't check right now, but I did check them before, and IIRC all the methods were listed. The issue was that there were _two_ primitive `char` pages (see my previous comment). I'll look into this, and include a link a github page with all the docs for the review of the final version of this PR. Thanks for the heads up!

@japaric 

> Alright, I'll look into it. One worry is that I think it may not be possible to `Int`/`Float` right off the bat, because they are used as bounds in some places (libtest comes to mind). So, I'll add the `impl u8/f32/etc` but leave those traits around. We can decide how to deal with them later, perhaps move them to rust-lang/num? Since I think libtest will also be moved out of rust-lang/rust.

Right, that's pretty much exactly the rollout plan I had in mind. Part of the motivation here is to do away with those traits within `std` itself, pushing this concern to the crates.io ecosystem. If you can introduce the inherent methods, I can take care of the rest.

@sfackler 

> Does rustdoc handle these impls in some non-terrible way?

Yes, they appear as a a normal `impl str` in [the primitive page](http://japaric.github.io/inherent/collections/primitive.str.html#representation). There is a link to the full preview docs in the top comment.

@nikomatsakis 

> Does that make sense to anyone else?

You voiced my view precisely, better than I was able to. Thanks!

> I believe slices, f32 and f64

I just realized that I need to move the `impl f32/f64` into libstd. This PRs puts them in libcore, but that way they don't provide inherent methods for math functions like `sin`, `cos`, etc.

@eddyb `str` has methods like `to_lowercase` that require allocation (returns a `String`) these are provided by `collections::StrExt`, but not by `core::StrExt`. A similar thing happens with `char`, the `unicode::CharExt` provides unicode-ish methods (`width`) that `core::CharExt` does not.

@alexcrichton so I was talking to @aturon about this a bit more and thinking about your claim regarding libcore. It seems like what you are saying, basically, is that it would be nice if there could be alternatives to libstd that lived in (say) cargo and which can be combined with libstd code. This is somewhat at odds with my "std is a root crate" concept. I think it's a noble goal, though it carries some downsides (namely, increased risk of fragmentation).

However, even if we did nothing else but standardize libcore, crates that rely on libstd could still interoperate with libstd, they just wouldn't enjoy inherent methods on integers and so forth. But we might also consider whether we want to integrate inherent methods into the trait system somehow so that it is possible to have multiple sets of "inherent" methods (and perhaps one must somehow pick-and-choose which one to use?). Variations on this theme have been requested over time.

I guess the important thing is that it doesn't seem like we're fundamentally ruling out the possibility of having a standardized libcore if we go this route. We are committing however to either having libstd get the benefit of inherent methods on scalar types while others don't, or else finding a way to bridge this gap in the future so that multiple sets of inherent methods can co-exist (which is probably going to wind up being somewhat similar to the trait scheme we have now).
